==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} ''[[streght]]'' (Anglo Saxon ''streht''), the past participle of Middle English ''strechen'' (Anglo-Saxon ''streccan''), to stretch.

===Pronunciation===
* {{SAMPA|/streIt/}}
* {{audio|en-us-straight.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|eɪt}}

====Homophones====
* [[strait]]

===Alternative spellings===
* [[streight]] (''obsolete'')

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|straighter|straightest}}

# Not [[crooked]] or [[bent]]; having a constant direction throughout its length.
#: ''a '''straight''' line''.
# Strictly along political lines.
#: ''He always votes a '''straight''' ticket''.
# Direct, truthful, frank.
#: ''a '''straight''' answer''.
# As it should be.
#: ''Everything is '''straight''' now''.
# Undiluted.
#: '''''straight''' whiskey.''
# Having all cylinders in a single row. (referring to an internal combustion engine)
#: ''a '''straight''' six.''
# ''[[slang]]'': conventional.
# ''[[slang]]'': heterosexual.
# ''[[slang]]'': satisfied.
# ''[[slang]]'': boring, unappealing, bad or of low quality.
# {{cricket}} On, or near a line running between the two [[wicket]]s.

====Antonyms====
* [[curved]]

====Usage notes====
* Straight is sometimes humorously used as meaning low quality by homosexuals and bisexuals, rather than [[gay]].

